Ah’m settlin’ doown…
Into a cryin’ shame…
An’ aw is lost

title: 03 Gales_ Who Knows What's In Store For Us Now__ Three Things For Strings_ III. Not What It Seems

Percussion, including timpani and cymbals, emphasizes key rhythmic points and builds tension. The piece begins with a slow, building introduction, gradually introducing more instruments and increasing in dynamic range. It features a clear song structure with distinct sections that build and release tension. The tempo is generally moderate, with some accelerandos and ritardandos to enhance the dramatic effect. title: 02 Gales_ Who Knows What's In Store For Us Now__ Three Things For Strings_ II. Kinda-Sorta
style: This instrumental piece is a high-energy, orchestral-electronic hybrid, primarily driven by a fast tempo and a complex arrangement. A prominent brass section provides powerful accents and counter-melodies, particularly in the lower register, adding depth and grandeur. Percussion includes a driving drum kit with a strong snare backbeat, complemented by orchestral percussion elements like timpani and cymbals for dramatic emphasis. Synthesizers contribute to the electronic texture with arpeggiated patterns and atmospheric pads, blending seamlessly with the acoustic instruments. The harmonic structure is largely tonal, with a sense of constant forward motion and occasional dramatic shifts. The production is clean and bright, with a wide stereo image and a balanced mix that allows each instrumental group to be clearly heard. The piece features a clear A-B-A-C-A structure, with recurring melodic themes and variations. The tempo is consistently fast, contributing to the urgent and exciting mood.

title: 01 Gales_ Who Knows What's In Store For Us Now__ Three Things For Strings_ I
style: This is an instrumental orchestral piece with a dramatic and suspenseful tone. The instrumentation primarily features strings, brass, and percussion. The string section carries the main melodic and harmonic content, often playing sustained chords and arpeggiated figures. The brass section provides powerful accents and reinforces the dramatic moments with fanfare-like motifs. Percussion, including timpani and cymbals, emphasizes rhythmic punctuation and builds tension. The piece features a dynamic range, moving from softer, more introspective passages to loud, full orchestral sections. The tempo is moderate, allowing for clear articulation of the melodic lines. The harmony is largely tonal, with occasional dissonances adding to the suspense. The overall structure appears to be through-composed, with evolving themes and variations rather than a strict verse-chorus form. The mixing places the strings prominently, with brass and percussion providing support and emphasis. Reverb is used to create a sense of space and grandeur.

title: Thank You (Cover)
style:
Teacup Parade in the Astral Laundromat
The refrigerator hums in lowercase italics,
while a spoon dreams of jazz in ultraviolet.
Every pigeon has an opinion on cloud geometry,
but none of them pay rent.
I stapled my thoughts to a passing balloon
and waved goodbye to logic —
she never liked parties anyway.
Bananas file lawsuits against gravity,
claiming emotional bruising.
Meanwhile, the moon reheats leftovers
from its last existential crisis.
A sock puppet recites Shakespeare to a cactus.
The cactus applauds politely,
then asks for a refund.
My heartbeat is a typewriter typing “whoops.”
Rain whispers rumors about the alphabet.
And somewhere,
in a parallel bowl of soup,
I finally remember the name of that feeling
that sounds like Tuesday.

title: Lunar Dude Boogie
style: Opens with quietly intense instrumental intro, followed by solos building into boldly fusing chopped and screwed techniques with Igbo Highlife guitar melodies, playful Klezmer clarinet, and pulsing Polka accordion, the track weaves Jersey Club rhythms and Miami Bass sub-bass with K-Pop synth gloss and Tropical House steel drums. The whole song ends with a gradually diminishing outro, instrumental bridge and coda.
